   215	
   216	``every(A).to(B).seconds`` executes the job function every N seconds such that A <= N <= B.
   217	
   218	
   219	Run a job until a certain time
   220	~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   221	
   222	.. code-block:: python
   223	
   224	    import schedule
   225	    from datetime import datetime, timedelta, time
   226	
   227	    def job():
   228	        print('Boo')
   229	
   230	    # run job until a 18:30 today
   231	    schedule.every(1).hours.until("18:30").do(job)
   232	
   233	    # run job until a 2030-01-01 18:33 today
   234	    schedule.every(1).hours.until("2030-01-01 18:33").do(job)
   235	
   236	    # Schedule a job to run for the next 8 hours
   237	    schedule.every(1).hours.until(timedelta(hours=8)).do(job)
   238	
   239	    # Run my_job until today 11:33:42
   240	    schedule.every(1).hours.until(time(11, 33, 42)).do(job)
   241	
   242	    # run job until a specific datetime
   243	    schedule.every(1).hours.until(datetime(2020, 5, 17, 11, 36, 20)).do(job)
   244	
   245	The ``until`` method sets the jobs deadline. The job will not run after the deadline.
   246	
   247	
   248	Run a job a limited number of times
   249	~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   250	
   251	.. code-block:: python
   252	
   253	    import schedule
   254	
   255	    def job():
   256	        print('Boo')
   257	
   258	    # Run the job three times, then cancel it.
   259	    schedule.every(1).hours.max_runs(3).do(job)
   260	
   261	The ``max_runs`` method cancels the job after the specified number of executions.
   262	
   263	
   264	Time until the next execution
   265	~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   266	Use ``schedule.idle_seconds()`` to get the number of seconds until the next job is scheduled to run.
   267	The returned value is negative if the next scheduled jobs was scheduled to run in the past.
   268	Returns ``None`` if no jobs are scheduled.
   269	
   270	.. code-block:: python
   271	
   272	    import schedule
   273	    import time
   274	
   275	    def job():

